1 Introduction

In this project I want to study laptop’s specifications and features, and its relation to the final price.

These features are mostly hardware, per instance, storage, RAM and graphic card. Also, some other attributes in the data are the brand and a few binary variables that explain if the laptop includes some software (MS office), warranty or if it has a touchscreen.

I want to know which variables condition price the most and by how much. I will try to fit a linear model for the price, because of the interpretability of the coefficients.

After learning which features matter the most for the laptop’s price, I will create a model that fits better the data than a linear model to predict the price of a laptopt. I will use some machine learning algorithms: K-Nearest Neighbors, Random Forest and Support Vector Machine.

The dataset contains other numerical variables like star rating, number of ratings and reviews, discount and older price. Since all this attributes are obtained after the laptop has been sold in the first place, they can’t be used to predict its price. I’m doing another project studying star ratings of laptops based on these same features and also considering the price and the discount.

Source: I downloaded the data from kaggle.com on 04/05/2020. New versions are available in:

https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/kuchhbhi/latest-laptop-price-list

The information in this data set was pulled from Flipkart, so the prices are in Indian rupees.

I converted all prices from rupees to Euros using a 1 to 0.012 ratio (exchange rate on 04/05/2020).

df$hdd <- as.factor(df$hdd)
df$hdd <- fct_collapse(df$hdd, "Yes" = c("512", "1024", "2048"), "No" = "0")

# grouping less frequent ssd's. Result: 5 categories. I'll group 32 and 128 with 256 (low size ssd) and 2048 and 3072 with 1024 (big ssd)
df$ssd <- as.factor(df$ssd)
df$ssd <- fct_collapse(df$ssd, "256" = c("32", "128", "256"), "1024" = c("1024", "2048", "3072"))

# dichotimic warranty variable, because over 90% of laptops with warranty have a 1 year warranty. Similar case as hdd.
df$warranty <- as.factor(df$warranty)
df$warranty <- fct_collapse(df$warranty, "Yes" = c("1", "2", "3"), "No" = "0")

# Reorder weight from light to heavy
df$weight <- fct_relevel(df$weight, c("ThinNlight", "Casual", "Gaming"))

# group under 20 freq. categories
df$graphic_card_gb <- as.factor(df$graphic_card_gb)
df$graphic_card_gb <- fct_collapse(df$graphic_card_gb, "6" = c("6", "8"))

# latest_price conversion to €
df$latest_price <- df$latest_price*0.012

# price naming
names(df)[names(df)=="latest_price"] <- "price"

3 Metadata

We want to know what features of a laptop contribute to a higher selling price. The variables for this study are:

name description data type range
price Selling price in euros Numerical continuous From 167 to 5304
brand Brand of the laptop Categorical nominal 8 most frequent brands or Other
hdd Whether it has a 1024GB HDD storage or not Binary No or Yes
sdd SSD capacity in GB Categorical ordinal “0”, “256”, “512”, “1024”
graphic card gb Video memory in GB Categorical ordinal “0”, “2”, “4” or “6”
ram gb RAM installed in GB Categorical ordinal “4”, “8” or “16”
processor brand Processor brand name Categorical nominal Intel, AMD, Apple or Other
weight Weight grouped into 3 classes Categorical ordinal ThinNlight, Casual or Gaming (heavy)
msoffice Microsoft Office pre-installed or not Binary No or Yes
touchscreen Whether it has touchscreen or not Binary No or Yes
warranty Includes a warranty or not Binary No or Yes

Target variable: price.

All the predictor variables are categorical. Some of them are ordinal which could be converted into integers (ram, sdd, graphic card and weight).

4 Price

The distribution of the price is asymmetric and skewed, with a right tail.

I will try to fit a Gamma distribution (common distribution for continuous with only positives values) and a log-normal distribution to the data.

summary(df$price)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##   167.9   545.9   761.9   915.7  1069.1  5303.9
### Estimating gamma parameters
scale_gam <- var(df$price)/mean(df$price) # mean(df$price) = E(X) = shape*scale
shape_gam <- mean(df$price)/scale_gam # var(df$price) = Var(X) = shape*scale^2

ggplot(df, aes(x=price)) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins=30, color = "black", fill="white")  + labs(title="Laptops' price distribution - fitting gamma distribution") + stat_function(fun=dgamma, args=list(shape=shape_gam, scale=scale_gam), col="blue")

ggplot(df, aes(x=log(price))) +
    geom_histogram(aes(y=..density..), bins=30, color = "black", fill="white")  + labs(title="Laptops' log(price) distribution - fitting normal distribution") + stat_function(fun=dnorm, args=list(mean=mean(log(df$price)), sd=sd(log(df$price))), col="blue")

If we transform the price with the logarithmic function, the distribution gets closer to a normal. I will use the log transformation quite often in this study, specially to compare prices for different categories of a variable.

The cheapest laptop costs 168€ and the most expensive has a selling price of 5304€. Half the laptops’ cost is between 545€ and 1069€, and the median price is around 762€.

More GB in the SSD means higher price for the laptop. Same happens for the graphic card and ram memories. On the other hand, having an HDD storage leads to lower price on the laptop. I will study if the laptops with an HDD are those that don’t have an SSD.

6.2 Exploring storage (HDD & SSD)

They are the two most used storage devices for computers nowadays. The initials stand for Hard Drive Disk or Solid State Drive.

As we have seen in the previous graphs, that cost on laptops gets higher with bigger storage disks.

It is known that SSD have a better performance than HDD, but they are more expensive.

Let’s check if that is true, by grouping the 2 storage attributes into 1 variable called “storage” with all the possible combinations.

df <- transform(df, storage=paste(hdd,ssd))
df$storage <- factor(df$storage, levels=c("No 0", "Yes 0", "No 256", "Yes 256", "No 512", "Yes 512", "No 1024"), 
                     labels=c("none", "1024hdd", "256ssd", "1024hdd_256ssd", "512ssd", "1024hdd_512ssd", "1024ssd"))
table(df$storage)
## 
##           none        1024hdd         256ssd 1024hdd_256ssd         512ssd 
##             64             88            140             74            411 
## 1024hdd_512ssd        1024ssd 
##              5            114

There are 64 laptops without any storage. It must be treated as NA since they must have a storage disk (missing information)

ggplot(df, aes(x=storage, y=log(price), fill=storage)) + geom_violin(alpha=0.5) + labs(y="price", x="storage", title="Price by storage") + geom_boxplot(width=0.1, fill="white") + scale_fill_manual(values=colrs) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position="none")

If we compare 1024GB hdd (2nd group) with 1024GB ssd (last group) laptops, we clearly see that ssd is way more expensive.

1024GB hdd and 256GB ssd devices have very similar price. Same happens for the price for 1024GB hhd + 256GB ssd laptops and those with only a 512GB ssd. And also 1024GB hdd + 512GB ssd’s price is very similar to 1024GB ssd laptops’.

Looks like the price for 256GB ssd is equivalent to the cost of a 1024GB hdd storage.

Since the prices are very similar for the pairs explained before, they could be grouped resulting in only 3 classes: “Small or Slow”, “Medium”, “Big or Fast”. I will try to name them ordering as “Sufficient”, “Good” and “Excellent”.

6.2.1 Grouping storage

To be sure of this, we can do a statistical test for a measure of central tendency between 2 independent samples.

T-test if they the price is normally distributed. Otherwise we can do Mann-Whitney non-parametric test.

df_low <- df %>% 
  filter(storage %in% c("1024hdd", "256ssd"))

wilcox.test(df_low$price  ~ fct_drop(df_low$storage, )) # Mann-Whitney U test for differences in price between 2 groups
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  df_low$price by fct_drop(df_low$storage, )
## W = 5602, p-value = 0.2502
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
med1 <- median(log(df_low[df_low$storage %in% "1024hdd", ]$price))
med2 <- median(log(df_low[df_low$storage %in% "256ssd", ]$price))

ggplot(df_low, aes(fill=storage, x=log(price))) + geom_density(alpha=0.4) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med1)) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med2)) + theme_bw()

We can consider that the first 2 groups have the same median price. The distribution also looks very similar.

I will name this group “Sufficient”.

df_medium <- df[df$storage %in% c("1024hdd_256ssd", "512ssd"),]
wilcox.test(df_medium$price  ~ df_medium$storage)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  df_medium$price by df_medium$storage
## W = 10638, p-value = 3.845e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
med3 <- median(log(df_medium[df_medium$storage %in% "1024hdd_256ssd", ]$price))
med4 <- median(log(df_medium[df_medium$storage %in% "512ssd", ]$price))

ggplot(df_medium, aes(fill=storage, x=log(price))) + geom_density(alpha=0.4) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med3)) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med4)) + theme_bw()

These 2 groups don’t look very similar and their medians are not that close. We can’t group them into one unique class. 512ssd has greater median than 1024hdd_256ssd laptops. I will name them “Good” and “Very good”, respectively.

df_high <- df[df$storage %in% c("1024hdd_512ssd", "1024ssd"),]
wilcox.test(df_high$price  ~ df_high$storage)
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  df_high$price by df_high$storage
## W = 208, p-value = 0.3109
## alternative hypothesis: true location shift is not equal to 0
table(df$storage)[levels(df$storage) %in% c("1024hdd_512ssd", "1024ssd")]

ggplot(df_high, aes(fill=storage, x=log(price))) + geom_density(alpha=0.4) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med5)) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med6)) + theme_bw()

These last two storage classes are somewhat similar. The top of the distribution for the price is close for each class, even though the 1024GB sdd has a tail on the right and the class 1024GB hdd + 512GB ssd has the tail on the left.

If we consider that the 2 classes are very imbalanced, makes sense to put the laptops from the less frequent class to the more frequent. I will rename this merged class to “Excellent”.

Conclusion of the grouping:

We can group 1024hdd with 256ssd and 1025hdd_512ssd with 1024ssd. The other categories left are “none”, 1024hdd_256ssd and 512ssd

So will we go from 7 categories (including NA) to only 5.

6.2.2 Filling NAs in storage

Are the NA random or non random?

As seen in the previous graphic with all the storage categories, the “none” storage laptops distribution for the price didn’t seem to be similar to the distribution of any specific class, so I believe they are random (the NA’s are not from just one class or only a few).

Let’s check if the price for this laptops is similar to all the other classes grouped into one.

ggplot(df_gr, aes(x=fct_other(storage, keep="none"), y=log(price), fill=fct_other(storage, keep="none"))) + geom_violin(alpha=0.5) + labs(y="log(price)", x="storage", title="Price by storage") + geom_boxplot(width=0.1, fill="white") + scale_fill_manual(values=colrs) + theme_bw() + theme(legend.position="none")

There seems to be more variance in the NAs. There are less laptops so it was to be expected.

The central tendency is very close for both cases. Nevertheless, the distribution of the NA’s has two local maximum points. They seem to be around a price of 245€ (exp(5.5)) or 1096€ (exp(7)) in contrast with the other laptops which tend to have a price of about exp(6.5) = 665€.

I think the best way to fill the NA’s is to classify each of these laptops into the class that has a nearer median.

So I just need to have all 4 medians calculated and then fill each NA laptop’s price with the nearest median value.

Another possibility would be doing K-Nearest Neighbors.

Filling the NA’s

df_NA <- df_gr[df_gr$storage == "none", c("price", "storage")]
price_NA <- log(df_NA$price)

med01 <- median(log(df_gr[df_gr$storage == "Sufficient", ]$price))
med02 <- median(log(df_gr[df_gr$storage == "Good", ]$price))
med03 <- median(log(df_gr[df_gr$storage == "Very good", ]$price))
med04 <- median(log(df_gr[df_gr$storage == "Excellent", ]$price))

similar <- c()
for(i in 1:length(price_NA)){
  v <- c(abs(price_NA[i] - med01), abs(price_NA[i] - med02), 
         abs(price_NA[i] - med03), abs(price_NA[i] - med04))
  similar[i] <- which.min(v)
}
similar <- factor(similar, labels=c("Sufficient", "Good", "Very good", "Excellent"))
table(similar)
## similar
## Sufficient       Good  Very good  Excellent 
##         27          5          7         25

Most laptops with NA on storage will be classified as “Sufficient” or “Excellent”.

# Before
table(df_no_fill$storage)
## 
##       none Sufficient       Good  Very good  Excellent 
##         64        228         74        411        119
# laptops[rownames(laptops) %in% rownames(df_NA) ,] # You can check the real storage with the brand and model
df_gr[rownames(df_gr) %in% rownames(df_NA),]$storage <- similar # fills the NA
df_gr$storage <- fct_drop(df_gr$storage) # remove "none" category
# After
table(df_gr$storage)
## 
## Sufficient       Good  Very good  Excellent 
##        255         79        418        144

6.3 Exploring brands

It would be interesting to reduce the amount of categories for this attributes for the later linear regression models. Especially those groups with very few instances. This is not really necessary when doing random forest.

Also, we want to group the “Other” category with the most similar one.

ggplot(df_gr, aes(fill=brand, x=log(price))) + geom_density(alpha=0.4) + theme_bw()

APPLE and DELL are definitely not groupable with any other class.

df_brand <- df_gr[!df_gr$brand %in% c("APPLE", "DELL"),]
ggplot(df_brand, aes(fill=brand, x=log(price))) + geom_density(alpha=0.4) + theme_bw()

# Kruskal Wallis test for 1 num dep. and multiple groups
kruskal.test(df_brand$price ~ df_brand$brand)
## 
##  Kruskal-Wallis rank sum test
## 
## data:  df_brand$price by df_brand$brand
## Kruskal-Wallis chi-squared = 16.095, df = 5, p-value = 0.006579

Kruskal Wallis test indicates that there is some difference between selling prices for the brands (at least 1 brand has different price that all the other ones).

6.3.1 Grouping brands

First I’ll try to group the “Other” category with another one

shapiro.test(log(df_brand[df_brand$brand =="Other", ]$price)) 
## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  log(df_brand[df_brand$brand == "Other", ]$price)
## W = 0.93589, p-value = 0.003562

Other laptops’s price is not normally distributed. Not even with the logarithmic transformation.

We need to do non-parametric test for comparing 2 median with 2 classes (Wilcoxon test).

# table(df_brand$brand)[3:6] # not balanced classes
df_brand1 <- df_brand[df_brand$brand %in% c("Other", "acer"),]
# Wilcoxon test for Other and Acer laptop prices
wilcox.test(df_brand1$price  ~ df_brand1$brand) 
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
## 
## data:  df_brand1$price by df_brand1$brand
## W = 1568.5, p-value = 0.3572

df_brand2 <- df_brand[df_brand$brand %in% c("Other", "HP"),]

wilcox.test(df_brand2$price  ~ df_brand2$brand) 
##

wilcox.test(df_brand3$price  ~ df_brand3$brand) 
## 
##  Wilcoxon rank sum test with continuity correction
##

ggplot(df_brand2, aes(fill=brand, x=log(price))) + geom_density(alpha=0.4) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med_br1)) + geom_vline(aes(xintercept=med_br3)) + theme_bw()

7 Multivariant qualitative (MCA/DCA)

Since all the independent variables to explain the price are categorical, I can do multiple correspondence analysis to see how the variables and their classes are related.

data_mca <- df_gr[, !names(df_gr) %in% 
                       c("processor_brand", "warranty", "msoffice")]
res.MCA <- MCA(data_mca, quanti.sup=1, quali.sup=c(5,6)
               , graph=F
               ) # method="Burt" gives CA on Burt table

8 Machine Learning models

8.1 Train-test sets

set.seed(14153)
trainIndex <- createDataPartition(df_gr$price, p = 2/3, list=F)
training <- df_gr[trainIndex, ]
testing <- df_gr[-trainIndex, ]
fitControl <- trainControl(method="repeatedcv", number=6, repeats=3)

In each cross validation, data is splitted into 6 parts (folds). 5 are used to create the model and 1 is for assessing the model.

8.2 Linear regression

Linear model with all the features. Remember they are all categorical, even though ram, graphic card, storage and weight could be treated as integers.

We want to model a numeric response variable depending on 9 categorical features. There are multiple options but the simplest one is a linear regression.

8.3 LM with cross validation

The most important features to determine the price of a laptop are storage, ram and graphic card. The brand, processor and weight also have some importance in the linear regression.

8.3.1 Coefficients interpretation

# Predicted price for the basic laptop
exp(summary(lm)$coefficients[1]) 
## [1] 370.802

The base laptop has this characteristics:

Brand = any but APPLE ; graphic_card_gb = 0; ram_gb = 4; processor_brand = Intel or APPLE;

weight = ThighNlight or Gaming ; touchscreen = No ; storage = Sufficient

These are also called the base category for each attribute.

Coefficients interpretation:

Increase in % if the variable has this category, compared to the base category. These are the coefficients that are significant for the model to predict the price:

(exp(summary(lm)$coefficients[-1, 1])-1)*100
##           brandAPPLE     graphic_card_gb2     graphic_card_gb4 
##            93.493699            15.022347            20.354700 
##     graphic_card_gb6              ram_gb8             ram_gb16 
##            42.329852            45.490252            86.796094 
##   processor_brandAMD processor_brandOther         weightCasual 
##           -10.862836            24.123472             3.826126 
##       touchscreenYes          storageGood   `storageVery good` 
##            31.181627            21.513832            29.533738 
##     storageExcellent 
##            96.416328

Brand: APPLE has an increase in price of 93% respect any other laptop brand.

Graphic card: the price increases in 15% for 2GB graphic cards, in 20% for 4GB graphic cards and in 42% for 6GB graphic card laptops.

Ram: the price gets increased by 45% if the laptop has a 8GB ram, and by 86% if the ram has 16GB, instead the basic 4GB ram.

If the processor for the laptop is AMD instead of Intel or APPLE, the price for the laptop will be 10% lower. If it is another one, then the price increases in 24%.

If the weight is Casual the price gets increased by 3%.

A laptop with touchscreen is 31% more expensive.

Having a “Good” storage instead of just “Sufficient” increases the price by 21%. A very good storage is slightly more expensive with an increment of 29% and an Excellent storage gets really expensive, with an increment of 96%.

8.4 Lasso regression

Useful for multicollinearity data (if we consider that ram, graphic card and storage are very related).

Lambda: strength of the penalty on the coefficients.

set.seed(63514)

               tuneGrid=expand.grid(alpha=1, lambda=seq(0.0001,0.01,length=5)),

Effect of Lambda

plot(lasso$finalModel, xvar="lambda", label=T)

As lambda gets relaxed the coefficients starts to grow, which means that RMSE will become larger. Increasing lambda helps reduce the size of the coefficients.

Looking at the graph, when log lambda is close to -2, there are only 2 coefficient in the model.

10 Conclusions

The features that inflate the price of laptops are storage, ram and graphic cards. Some brands add value to its laptops (for instance, Apple). Furthermore, touchscreen laptops are more expensive.

This study would have been much better with more information about the processor, for example, knowing the generation of Intel processors. Unfortunately, the data set has a lot of wrong values in this variable.

With this data, it is possible to study which laptops are liked most with a variable called star rating (that goes from 0 to 5). This will be my next project.
